{"title_page": "Boxley Abbey", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n[[File:Remains of Boxley Abbey and North Downs - geograph.org.uk - 1101929.jpg|thumb|Remains of Boxley Abbey and [[North Downs]]]]\n'''Boxley Abbey''' in [[Boxley]], [[Kent]], England was a [[Cistercian]] monastery founded c.1146 by [[William of Ypres]], leader of King Stephen's Flemish mercenaries, and colonised by monks from [[Clairvaux Abbey]] in France. Some of its ruins survive, some four miles north-east of [[Maidstone]].\n\n== Notable events ==\n\nIn 1171, the then abbot was one of those responsible for the burial of the murdered archbishop of Canterbury, [[Thomas Becket]]. In 1193 the abbots of Boxley and [[Robertsbridge Abbey|Robertsbridge]] journeyed to the continent to search for [[King Richard I]], finally locating him in [[Bavaria]]. During 1512-13, the abbot appealed to the crown to arrest four of the monks, accusing them of rebelliousness.\n\n== The relics ==\n\n[[Image:A fragment of a medieval lead alloy pilrgim badge from the Rood of Grace at Boxley Abbey dating to the 15th century. (FindID 587463).jpg|thumb|Fragment of [[Lead#Elemental form|cast-lead]] pilgrims' badge (showing front and back) depicting the Rood]]The abbey was famous, and later infamous, for a [[relic]] known as the [[Rood of Grace]], a wooden cross, the figure upon which was supposed to miraculously move and speak. In 1538 during the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]] one Geoffrey Chamber,  a \"commissioner\" employed by [[Thomas Cromwell]] to oversee the closure of the institution, examined the famed relic and discovered it to be a fake, observing the levers and wires that enacted the so-called miracles.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gairdner|first1=James|authorlink=James Gairdner|title=Lollardy and the Reformation in England: An Historical Survey|date=1911|publisher=Macmillan|location=London|page=122|volume=3}}</ref> The rood was taken down and displayed in [[Maidstone]] market so as to demonstrate the fraud. Finally, it was sent to [[London]] and with the accompaniment of a sermon from the [[Bishop of Rochester]] it was hacked to pieces and burnt. There is no evidence that any miracles were ever associated with the moving image, notwithstanding the monks' practice of infiltrating hired imposters into the throng to celebrate the supposed cures.<ref>{{cite book|last=Reeves|first=Margaret|display-authors=et al|title=Shell Games: Studies in Scams, Frauds, and Deceits (1300-1650)|date=28 April 2001|publisher=Victoria University|location=Toronto, Canada|isbn=9780772720238|page=11}}</ref> However, the presence of wires and levers in themselves does not constitute fraud;<ref>''The Antiquary,'' [https://books.google.com/books?id=BisFAAAAQAAJ&source Volume 8 (1883), pp. 48\u201352] and [https://books.google.com/books?id=AeE-AQAAMAAJ&dq Volume 25 (1892), p. 183]</ref> theatrical historian Leanne Groeneveld contends that this \"puppetry\" was presented as a theatrical show to a fully cognisant audience.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Groeneveld|first1=Leanne|title=A Theatrical Miracle: The Boxley Rood of Grace as Puppet|journal=Early Theatre|date=2007|volume=10.2|pages=11\u201350|issn=1206-9078}}</ref>\n\nA legend that an effigy of the infant [[Rumwold of Buckingham|Saint Rumbold]] could only be lifted from its plinth by the particularly righteous was exploited by the monks, who engaged or disengaged a hidden spring under the statue, according to the size of the cash gift on offer.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cartwright|first1=Julia|title=The Pilgrims' Way: From Winchester to Canterbury|date=1911|publisher=John Murray|location=London|oclc=559472322|chapter=Kits Coty House|authorlink=Julia Cartwright Ady}}</ref> The supposed finger of the [[Andrew the Apostle|apostle Andrew]], inlaid heavily with silver, was also on display but was pawned to a local merchant for eleven pounds when the flow of \"credulous and devout\" visitors ceased.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Roberts|first1=Barr\u00e8 Charles|title=Miscellaneous Papers|date=1814|publisher=Bulmer|location=London|oclc=475425604|pages=190\u2013192|chapter=History of Boxley Abbey}}</ref>\n\n== The Dissolution and beyond ==\n[[File:Ruins of Boxley Abbey gateway.jpg|thumb|Ruins of the Abbey's gateway]]\nThe abbey appears to have been \"surrendered\" to the king, or dissolved, on 29 January 1537 (in the 28th year of the reign on Henry.) The site of the abbey and many of its manorial estates were granted to [[Thomas Wyatt (poet)|Sir Thomas Wyatt]] in 1540. After the dissolution some of the complex was transformed into a house with the remainder virtually demolished. Parts survive within the present mainly 19th-century house, and there are some fragmentary remains of the church still standing. [[Boxley Abbey Barn]], a large 13th-century stone building which served as the abbey's [[Hospitium#Medieval Hospitia|Hospitium]] remains. It is a Grade I [[listed building]].<ref name=NHLE>{{NHLE |num=1086229 |desc=Barn at Boxley Abbey |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> The precinct of the abbey is a [[scheduled monument]].<ref>{{NHLE |num=1012264 |desc=Cistercian Abbey at Boxley |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> The site is private. The parish church of [[St Mary's and All Saints Church, Boxley|St Mary and All Saints]] was associated with the abbey.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=BisFAAAAQAAJ&source The Antiquary, Volume 8 (1883), p. 49.]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of scheduled monuments in Maidstone]]\n omg u can edit this sight is not safe dont use\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* ''Houses of Cistercian monks: The abbey of Boxley'', A History of the County of Kent: Volume 2 (1926), pp.&nbsp;153\u201355.\n* Anthony New. ''A Guide to the Abbeys of England And Wales'', p75-76. Constable.\n\n{{coord|51.300154|0.524790|region:GB_type:landmark|format=dms|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Cistercian monasteries in England]]\n[[Category:Monasteries in Kent]]\n[[Category:1140s establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in the 1140s]]\n[[Category:1540 disestablishments in England]]\n[[Category:Christian monasteries established in the 12th century]]\n[[Category:Monasteries dissolved under the English Reformation]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n[[File:Remains of Boxley Abbey and North Downs - geograph.org.uk - 1101929.jpg|thumb|Remains of Boxley Abbey and [[North Downs]]]]\n'''Boxley Abbey''' in [[Boxley]], [[Kent]], England was a [[Cistercian]] monastery founded c.1146 by [[William of Ypres]], leader of King Stephen's Flemish mercenaries, and colonised by monks from [[Clairvaux Abbey]] in France. Some of its ruins survive, some four miles north-east of [[Maidstone]].\n\n== Notable events ==\n\nIn 1171, the then abbot was one of those responsible for the burial of the murdered archbishop of Canterbury, [[Thomas Becket]]. In 1193 the abbots of Boxley and [[Robertsbridge Abbey|Robertsbridge]] journeyed to the continent to search for [[King Richard I]], finally locating him in [[Bavaria]]. During 1512-13, the abbot appealed to the crown to arrest four of the monks, accusing them of rebelliousness.\n\n== The relics ==\n\n[[Image:A fragment of a medieval lead alloy pilrgim badge from the Rood of Grace at Boxley Abbey dating to the 15th century. (FindID 587463).jpg|thumb|Fragment of [[Lead#Elemental form|cast-lead]] pilgrims' badge (showing front and back) depicting the Rood]]The abbey was famous, and later infamous, for a [[relic]] known as the [[Rood of Grace]], a wooden cross, the figure upon which was supposed to miraculously move and speak. In 1538 during the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]] one Geoffrey Chamber,  a \"commissioner\" employed by [[Thomas Cromwell]] to oversee the closure of the institution, examined the famed relic and discovered it to be a fake, observing the levers and wires that enacted the so-called miracles.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ga