posed finger of the [[Andrew the Apostle|apostle Andrew]], inlaid heavily with silver, was also on display but was pawned to a local merchant for eleven pounds when the flow of \"credulous and devout\" visitors ceased.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Roberts|first1=Barr\u00e8 Charles|title=Miscellaneous Papers|date=1814|publisher=Bulmer|location=London|oclc=475425604|pages=190\u2013192|chapter=History of Boxley Abbey}}</ref>\n\n== The Dissolution and beyond ==\n[[File:Ruins of Boxley Abbey gateway.jpg|thumb|Ruins of the Abbey's gateway]]\nThe abbey appears to have been \"surrendered\" to the king, or dissolved, on 29 January 1537 (in the 28th year of the reign on Henry.) The site of the abbey and many of its manorial estates were granted to [[Thomas Wyatt (poet)|Sir Thomas Wyatt]] in 1540. After the dissolution some of the complex was transformed into a house with the remainder virtually demolished. Parts survive within the present mainly 19th-century house, and there are some fragmentary remains of the church still standing. [[Boxley Abbey Barn]], a large 13th-century stone building which served as the abbey's [[Hospitium#Medieval Hospitia|Hospitium]] remains. It is a Grade I [[listed building]].<ref name=NHLE>{{NHLE |num=1086229 |desc=Barn at Boxley Abbey |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> The precinct of the abbey is a [[scheduled monument]].<ref>{{NHLE |num=1012264 |desc=Cistercian Abbey at Boxley |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> The site is private. The parish church of [[St Mary's and All Saints Church, Boxley|St Mary and All Saints]] was associated with the abbey.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=BisFAAAAQAAJ&source The Antiquary, Volume 8 (1883), p. 49.]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of scheduled monuments in Maidstone]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* ''Houses of Cistercian monks: The abbey of Boxley'', A History of the County of Kent: Volume 2 (1926), pp.&nbsp;153\u201355.\n* Anthony New. ''A Guide to the Abbeys of England And Wales'', p75-76. Constab